Share this Story: United Way of SDG Community Campaign supporting more agencies

United Way of SDG Community Campaign supporting more agencies Photo by Francis Racine / Francis Racine/Standard-Freeholder

Article content The United Way/Centraide of SDG in its 2020-21 welcomed three new member agencies to the fold when it made its funding announcement recently. Joining the list of agencies receiving funding are Diversity Cornwall, Community Information Centre of Ottawa-211 EAST, and Centre Charles-Emile-Claude. We apologize, but this video has failed to load. Try refreshing your browser. United Way of SDG Community Campaign supporting more agencies Back to video In a recent news release, United Way/Centraide of SDG executive director Juliette Labossiere said this year’s investment totals $337,786, a slight increase from last year, and that with new member agencies and programs being supported, the United Way’s impact in the community will grow. “We’re excited and proud to grow our membership,” Labossiere said. “These new agencies hold the potential to allow us to reach thousands of new individuals, and help some of the most vulnerable members of our community.” The United Way recently completed the allocations process for its traditional stream of funding, the investments above and beyond recent announcements on funding regarding the COVID-19 crisis. With all of its member agencies and programs back from last year, a total of 20 different programs in the region are receiving financial support.

Advertisement Story continues below This advertisement has not loaded yet, but your article continues below.

Article content The allocations process is volunteer driven, led by United Way board members, who evaluate each member agency’s request for funding and then make a recommendation. The board of directors finalizes the annual amounts each member agency receives. Funding for allocations usually comes entirely from the amounts raised during the ongoing annual campaign. The community campaign had its annual launch in mid-September with a kickoff breakfast at Royal Canadian Legion Branch 297 in Cornwall. As at the previous two breakfasts, the United Way didn’t announce a financial goal, instead focusing on the agencies it supports and how their need is year-round. There was one announced contribution, the RBC Foundation getting the campaign off to a big start with a $12,500 donation. The campaign continues year-round, but in mid-March the pandemic arrived, and the United Way became an even more important part of the region’s social support structure. More On This Topic Over $330,000 in emergency community funds for Cornwall area A massive grocery hamper project begins in Cornwall/SDG/Akwesasne United Way/Centraide of SD&G launches annual campaign The Regional Emergency Response Council (RERC) was formed, co-chaired by Labossiere and Social Development Council of Cornwall and Area executive director Carilyne Hebert. And late in May, over $330,000 in emergency community funds provided by the federal government, with the United Way and RERC working together and collaborating with the government to support those in need.

Advertisement Story continues below This advertisement has not loaded yet, but your article continues below.

Article content But that community campaign always exists, and it’s vital for many local agencies and groups. “Since the start of the COVID-19 crisis we’ve been in the news quite a bit in regards to our work for the (RERC),” Labossiere said. “We’re proud to continue that work, but are thankful for our strong and dedicated volunteers who remained active on our (Community Campaign) Allocation Committee and pursued our traditional work in the background. “We know the need after this crisis will grow compared to last year, and we can’t thank the community enough for supporting us in the 2019 Campaign and allowing us to support so many great organizations that will be ready to help when the crisis subsides.” Returning member agencies receiving funds from the community campaign are as follows (United Way did not disclose the individual amounts): Boys & Girls Club of Cornwall/SDG;

Equipe Psycho-sociale;

Meals on Wheels Cornwall;

Inspire (formally SD&G Developmental Services and Counselling Support Services of SD&G);

Glengarry Inter-Agency Group;

Sexual Assault Support Services of Cornwall/SDG/Akwesasne:

Canadian Hearing;

Tri-County Literacy Council;

Upper Canada Leger Centre for Education and Training;

Big Brothers Big Sisters of Cornwall and District;

Canadian Mental Health Association-Champlain East;

Beyond 21; and,

Centre 105.

